## üåü Tailwind CSS RTL Support Rule for Cursor Editor üåü

To ensure full Right-to-Left (RTL) support in your code, especially when using Tailwind CSS, you must utilize **CSS Logical Properties** which are extensively supported by newer versions of Tailwind (v3.3+). This approach maintains cleaner code and automatically adjusts styling based on the `dir="rtl"` attribute set on the `<html>` tag or parent elements.

-----

### 1\. Prioritize Logical Classes (Start and End)

Instead of using classes that directly reference physical directions (Left and Right), use their logical equivalents (Start and End).

| Physical Direction (LTR-Specific) | Logical Equivalent (RTL/LTR Supported) | Description |
| :---: | :---: | :---: |
| `ml-`, `mr-` | `ms-`, `me-` | **Margin** Start / End |
| `pl-`, `pr-` | `ps-`, `pe-` | **Padding** Start / End |
| `left-`, `right-` | `start-`, `end-` | Positioning |
| `border-l-`, `border-r-` | `border-s-`, `border-e-` | Border Start / End |
| `rounded-l-`, `rounded-r-` | `rounded-s-`, `rounded-e-` | Rounded Corners Start / End |
| `text-left`, `text-right` | `text-start`, `text-end` | Text Alignment |
| `float-left`, `float-right` | `float-start`, `float-end` | Floating |

> **Example:**
>
> ‚ùå Instead of `pl-2` (Padding Left), use: **`ps-2`** (Padding Start)
>
> ‚ùå Instead of `mr-4` (Margin Right), use: **`me-4`** (Margin End)
>
> ‚ùå Instead of `text-right`, use: **`text-end`**

-----

### 2\. Use `rtl:` and `ltr:` Variants for Exceptions

If, for any reason, you require a different style for a specific direction (LTR or RTL) and a logical class equivalent is unavailable or impractical, use the `rtl:` and `ltr:` variants.

  * **`rtl:`**: Style applied **only** when the document direction is set to **RTL** (e.g., `<html dir="rtl">`).
  * **`ltr:`**: Style applied **only** when the document direction is set to **LTR** (the default).

| Scenario | LTR Class (Default) | RTL Class (Exception) |
| :---: | :---: | :---: |
| Need `margin-left` in LTR and `margin-right` in RTL | `ml-4 rtl:mr-4` | (If a logical class isn't suitable) |
| Need a specific style only in RTL | `... rtl:border-red-500` | (Adding a red border only in RTL mode) |

> **Crucial Note:** Always attempt to use logical classes (`ps-2`, `text-start`) first. Limit the use of `rtl:` or `ltr:` variants to cases where a direct logical equivalent does not exist or an exceptional, explicit directional behavior is required.

-----

### 3\. Ensure Global Direction Setting

For logical classes and directional variants to work correctly, the `dir` attribute **must** be set on the `<html>` tag:

```html
<html dir="rtl">
    </html>
```

-----

### üìù Summary of Rule for Cursor Editor

When editing or writing Tailwind CSS classes:

1.  **Logical First:** Always replace physical classes like `ml-`, `mr-`, `pl-`, `pr-`, `text-left`, `text-right` with their logical counterparts: **`ms-`, `me-`, `ps-`, `pe-`, `text-start`, `text-end`**, etc.
2.  **Variants for Exceptions:** Only use **`rtl:` and `ltr:`** variants when a logical class is not available or if a specific, exceptional style rule is mandatory for one direction.
